covered: Valid Request: Successful updates (TC01, TC02) with 204 and verified persistence.
existing Resource Handling: Non-Existing Resource (TC08) and Invalid accountId format (TC06).
Partial Update: Partial input scenarios (TC03, TC04, TC19).
Error Handling: System error (TC12) and invalid data/header cases (TC07, TC05, TC18, TC21).
Boundary/Edge Cases: Empty body (TC11), Large payloads (TC13), Slow network/timeout (TC14), Extra fields (TC10), Extra query params (TC22).
Security/Authorization: Unauthorized update (TC09) and header requirements (TC05, TC02).
Data Validation: Invalid data in body (TC07), invalid accountId (TC06), injection (TC18).
Performance/Regression: Large payload performance (TC13) and regression for email-only update (TC15).
Notes: Comprehensive coverage of typical PUT lifecycle scenarios including success, client errors, server errors, and resilience scenarios.
gaps: Authorization/Access control edge case coverage could be expanded with explicit 403 vs 401 distinctions in different contexts.
Caching behavior (ETag, Cache-Control) not tested for PUT responses.
Rate limiting/throttling for bursts of PUT requests not covered.
Explicit 404 vs 400 differentiation for non-existent resource is driven by the story; current TC08 uses 400 but could include a scenario asserting 404 when appropriate.
Pagination is not relevant for PUT, so no tests needed, but guideline mentions pagination generally; alignment note: not applicable for this PUT context.
recommendations: Add explicit tests for rate limiting/throttling of sequential PUT requests to assess resilience under bursts.
Add a dedicated test verifying caching headers on PUT responses (ETag/Cache-Control) to satisfy caching guidance, where applicable.
Clarify and possibly extend authorization edge cases to include scenarios where different roles/permissions affect PUT outcomes (e.g., 403).
Consider a dedicated 404 test for non-existent resources if the API semantics prefer 404 over 400 in this scenario, to avoid ambiguity.
